  "prompt": "How do deaf people communicate?",
  "response": "Deaf people communicate in various ways, depending on their individual preferences, background, and the resources available to them. Here are some common methods of communication used by deaf individuals:\n\n1. **Sign Language**: Many deaf individuals use sign language as their primary mode of communication. Different regions have their own sign languages, such as American Sign Language (ASL), British Sign Language (BSL), or Auslan (Australian Sign Language). These languages have their own grammatical rules and vocabulary.\n\n2. **Gestures and Facial Expressions**: In addition to formal sign languages, many deaf individuals use gestures and facial expressions to convey meaning and emotions. These can include pointing, using iconic gestures, and employing non-manual markers like facial expressions to indicate tones or questions.\n\n3. **Written Communication**: Some deaf people prefer to communicate through writing, whether by texting, emailing, or writing notes. This method can be especially useful in environments where sign language cannot be used.\n\n4. **Speech and Lip Reading**: Some deaf individuals use spoken language and may rely on lip reading to understand what others are saying. This can be more common among those who have hearing loss later in life or who were raised in hearing families.\n\n5. **Assistive Technology**: Various technologies can aid in communication, such as video relay services (VRS) that allow deaf individuals to communicate via video calls with interpreters, text-to-speech apps, and hearing aids or cochlear implants for those who have some residual hearing.\n\n6. **Communication Access Real-time Translation (CART)**: This service provides real-time transcription of spoken language into text, allowing deaf individuals to read what is being said during meetings, lectures, or presentations.\n\n7. **Interpreters**: Many deaf people use sign language interpreters for more complex communications, such as legal settings, medical appointments, or educational environments.\n\nEach individual's preferred communication method can vary, and many deaf people are multilingual, using a combination of the above methods. The choice of communication often depends on a person's cultural background, level of hearing loss, education, and personal experiences.",
